<p>Once I was in an interview, and I was asked what motivated me. My answer was momentum. And maybe thatŌĆÖs why working with AI can be so engaging sometimes. And maybe itŌĆÖs also why it could be so frustrating. When we feel like we have momentum and weŌĆÖre moving more quickly than usual, thatŌĆÖs motivating. But when youŌĆÖre stuck and you canŌĆÖt get the LLM to do what you want it to, despite prompting in 5 different ways, itŌĆÖs frustrating.</p>

<p>A lot of times, we end up figuring it out and then we call the session ŌĆ£productive.ŌĆØ We completed the task, shipped the thing, and then weŌĆÖre off to the next thin.</p>

<p>But I think we need to pause at productivity and dig into that a little deeper. Because if productivity is the metric of success, weŌĆÖre missing a whole layer of work weŌĆÖre doing.</p>

<p>For example, over a ten day period I worked with Claude Code building, iterating, experimenting, shipping, documenting. I definitely had some of those frustrating moments, and it was important to me that I learned from those sessions and where I was getting frustrated. I had been running the session with <a href="tapes.dev">tapes</a>, so I had session recordings with replay of everything I had done. That was 426 messages. 13.1 tokens. And a whole lot of data to figure out what was happening.</p>

<p>ItŌĆÖs never just a user sending a message and the agent responding. ItŌĆÖs alignment, clarification, confirmation, iteratation, an ongoing labor of getting Claude and me to operate from the same reality long enough to move the work forward.</p>

<p>What I found was that probably under 40% of those sessions were actually work. ItŌĆÖs not to say that the other 60% was a failure. The session was productive in the way that most of us mean that word. But the data tells a more honest story. I learned about how much invisible work hides inside an AI workflow, and how alignment tax impacts the quickest way to success.</p>

<h2 id="i-didnt-think-this-was-a-problem">I didnŌĆÖt think this was a problem</h2>

<p>Thinking back about my own experience, I was thinking more about the outputs than about what was happening because nothing was breaking <em>eventually</em> I was getting what I was asking for. Sure, I was looking at things like how fast it was completed and how many tokens were being used, but I wasnŌĆÖt looking closely enough about what was happening in the conversation.</p>

<p>I was describing a task, the llm was giving me something close to what I meant, but not quite. So I corrected it, it adjusted, I attempted to verify the results, noticed filenames didnŌĆÖt match, I fixed the reference, checked the directory, and confirmed the output.</p>

<p>So to sum this up a bit, I was doing two things at once:</p>

<ol>
  <li>moving the task forward</li>
  <li>establishing the shared context the task depends on.</li>
</ol>

<p>Those arenŌĆÖt the same kinds of work, the alignment tax. Those are the extra cycles spent not on the work itself, but on establishing the shared reality required for the work.</p>

<p>In my case, the model didnŌĆÖt recognize my file naming conventions. It didnŌĆÖt understand my visual references. It didnŌĆÖt know which assumptions were safe and which ones were going to cost me another three turns. I knew some of that. I didnŌĆÖt know some of it until the model guessed wrong and exposed the gap. ThatŌĆÖs the part IŌĆÖm interested in here to help me work more deliberately.</p>

<p>HereŌĆÖs what I mean. I gave the model a straightforward task: place images in the blog post. It created placeholder image paths that made sense based on the information it had. We can call it ŌĆ£reasonable defaults.ŌĆØ So, in a narrow sense, the task was done. The problem was that it didnŌĆÖt use the images I had already uploaded. It created placeholder paths instead of the actual path. So instead of linking to <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">ai-llms-model.svg</code>, I got <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">ai-llm-model.svg</code>. And a similar scenario for the other images. Nothing dramatic, but another check and correction for a ŌĆ£simpleŌĆØ task, which meant the task was technically completed twice: once against assumptions and once in reality.</p>

<p>When I went back and looked at the tapes data, it looked like this:</p>

